"To be precise, there are two ways to go about calculating the margin of error for survey data—using an exact confidence interval or an approximate confidence interval. The former takes into account both sam- pling and non-sampling errors, while the latter only accounts for random sampling errors. While the exact interval may be more precise, we find the advantages of the approximate confidence interval to far outweigh the drawbacks, in particular with respect to the efficiency of the calculation. Moreover, we have no reason to suspect that there is any bias created by certain groups being excluded or not being forthright in their responses, so compensating for such error is simply beyond our reach. Thus we report an approximate confidence interval for each region's QoG estimate.",
